# Agent contract — {{ project_name }}

This repository runs the infrastructure of **{{ community_name }}**:
a single-node k3s cluster on {{ server_ipv4 }} ({{ target_arch }}), GitOps
via Argo CD, central identity via ZITADEL at `id.{{ domain }}`. It is generated
from [agentops-community-stack](https://github.com/levino/agentops-community-stack)
and is designed so that **you, the agent, can build and operate it from
zero** — the human is product owner, not operator.

Read this file first. For any non-trivial operation there is a runbook:

- Build everything from scratch: `runbooks/bootstrap-from-zero.md`
- Known footguns (read BEFORE debugging): `runbooks/incidents/`
- Argo CD git auth (GitHub App, per-org credential): `runbooks/argocd-github-app.md`
- PR previews (ApplicationSet PullRequest generator): `patterns/app-preview-prs/`
- ZITADEL bootstrap secrets: `zitadel/SECRETS.md`
- ZITADEL identity content (API, not git): `runbooks/zitadel-identity-via-api.md`
- Identity bootstrap (tofu, minimal): `tofu/zitadel/README.md`
- Adding apps: `apps/README.md` and `patterns/`
- Login v2, external IdPs, role→groups, oauth2-proxy+nginx, public/protected
  sites: `patterns/`

## Invariants (hard rules — never break, never "temporarily" bypass)

1. **GitOps is the single source of truth.** No manual `kubectl apply`
   outside the documented bootstrap steps. To change the cluster, change
   this repo. If you find drift, fix the repo, not the cluster.
2. **Never `cluster-admin` for CI/OIDC identities.** CI identities get the
   `preview-deployer` ClusterRole via namespace-scoped RoleBinding only
   (`scripts/new-app.sh` does this correctly). This is **enforced**, not just
   asked: `cluster/policy/` ships a ValidatingAdmissionPolicy that denies
   binding `cluster-admin` to any User/Group subject at admission time — you
   cannot bypass it by hand.
3. **Two classes of secret, two homes — never mix them.**
   - **Service/app secrets** (third-party API keys, database passwords, an
     app's own OIDC client secret, the oauth2-proxy cookie secret) belong to
     an app and rotate with it. These — and ONLY these — enter the repo as
     **SealedSecrets**: seal offline against `sealed-secrets-public-key.pem`,
     commit the sealed blob next to the app.
   - **Infrastructure credentials** (above all the Argo CD git-auth GitHub App
     key — see inv. 4 — and any ZITADEL operator credential — see inv. 6)
     live **ONLY in the cluster**, created directly with `kubectl` — **NEVER
     in git, not even sealed.** A sealed infra credential leaves a permanent
     encrypted blob in history forever and is not what SealedSecrets are for.
     Accepted trade-off (documented, not a bug): these secrets are **not**
     reproducible from git and must be **recreated by hand at cluster
     rebuild** — the bootstrap and `runbooks/argocd-github-app.md` cover how.
   Never commit plaintext, never echo secrets into logs.
4. **Argo CD git authentication is ALWAYS a GitHub App — NEVER a PAT.** Create
   one GitHub App per instance, named `Server {{ community_name }}` (or
   `Server <org>`), install it **separately on every org** whose repos Argo CD
   must read (`contents: read`, plus `pull requests: read` for PR previews),
   and register it as an Argo CD **`repo-creds`** secret in the `argocd`
   namespace holding `githubAppID` / `githubAppInstallationID` /
   `githubAppPrivateKey`, keyed by the org's URL prefix. The installation ID is
   **per-org** (one credential per org, same key, that org's installation
   ID); the private key is shared across installs. A GitHub App is scoped,
   centrally revocable and mints short-lived tokens — a PAT is a broad,
   personal, long-lived credential and must not be used. These App secrets
   are infrastructure credentials: created directly in the cluster, never
   committed (inv. 3). PUBLIC repos need no credential at all. Full recipe:
   `runbooks/argocd-github-app.md`.
5. **Images must run on {{ target_arch }} — built on NATIVE runners, never
   QEMU.** Build each architecture on its own native GitHub runner
   (`ubuntu-24.04-arm` for arm64, `ubuntu-latest` for amd64) and merge them
   into one manifest list with `docker buildx imagetools create`. Do NOT use
   QEMU/cross-emulation (`docker/setup-qemu-action`, or a single-job
   `platforms: linux/amd64,linux/arm64` build) — it is slow and has shipped
   broken images here. A pull that works on your machine proves nothing.
6. **ZITADEL identity content is API-managed at runtime — NOT in tofu/git.**
   Projects, roles, OIDC clients, external IdPs and **above all who is in
   which group/role (user grants)** are managed through the **ZITADEL API**,
   not committed as code. Two reasons: (a) **GDPR** — personal membership
   data must never live in version control (it is hard to delete, gets
   replicated, persists in history); (b) it changes far too often for a code
   loop. `tofu/zitadel/` holds at most the bare instance/org bootstrap. The
   API credential is a ZITADEL **service-user PAT held by the operator** and
   passed per session — it is **never stored in the cluster** (no
   service-account key, no PAT as a k8s secret). See `tofu/zitadel/README.md`
   and `runbooks/zitadel-identity-via-api.md`.
7. **ZITADEL is an IdP, not a CRM.** Domain data (fees, join dates,
   membership numbers) belongs in app databases, keyed by the token `sub`.
8. **Single node, single replica is a feature** (cheap infra). Do not add
   HA machinery.

## Layout

| Path | What | Propagation |
|---|---|---|
| `argocd/` | GitOps entry point (AppProject + Helm repo sources + root "app of apps") | applied once at bootstrap, then self-managed |
| `argocd/applications/` | child Applications: traefik, cluster, zitadel(-base/-postgresql), apps | Argo CD |
| `cluster/` | substrate: cert-manager, sealed-secrets, rbac, policy (cluster-admin guardrail) | Argo CD (Application `cluster`) |
| `zitadel/` | ZITADEL namespace + sealed bootstrap secrets (ZITADEL/Postgres are Helm Applications) | Argo CD (Application `zitadel-base` — OutOfSync until secrets are sealed) |
| `apps/` | one entry per app — stamped by `scripts/new-app.sh` | Argo CD (Application `apps`) |
| `tofu/zitadel/` | ZITADEL **bootstrap only** (instance/org); identity content is API-managed (inv. 6) | `tofu apply` (local), once |
| `patterns/` | copyable recipes: native OIDC, ForwardAuth, PR previews, login v2, external IdP, role→groups, oauth2-proxy+nginx, public/protected sites, app deploy CI | read, copy, adapt |
| `runbooks/` | bootstrap, Argo CD GitHub App, ZITADEL-via-API, incidents | read |

## Verify commands (use these before declaring anything healthy)

```bash
kubectl -n argocd get applications   # all SYNC=Synced, HEALTH=Healthy
                                     # (zitadel-base stays OutOfSync until sealed)
kubectl get pods -A | grep -v Running | grep -v Completed   # should be empty
kubectl get certificates -A      # all Ready=True
curl -fsS https://id.{{ domain }}/.well-known/openid-configuration | head -3
kubectl describe node | grep -A5 Conditions   # no DiskPressure (see incidents/)
```

(With the Argo CD CLI logged in, `argocd app list` shows the same.)

## Operating rules of thumb

- A change is deployed when Argo CD has reconciled it — verify with
  `kubectl -n argocd get applications` (Synced/Healthy), not by assuming.
- If an Application's Helm sync hangs >30s in install: pull the pod logs of its
  init/setup hooks IMMEDIATELY (see `runbooks/incidents/zitadel-bootstrap.md`,
  lesson learned).
- After every real incident: write `runbooks/incidents/<date>-<slug>.md`
  (what happened, root cause, fix, prevention). If the lesson generalizes,
  open a PR against the template repo — that is the feedback loop.
- The issuer is named `acme` in every environment. Do not rename it, do not
  hardcode ACME URLs anywhere outside `cluster/cert-manager/issuer.yaml`.
